{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648727"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:56:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:56:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18330"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18330"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11048"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74275"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11048"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59766"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7438"},{"type":"tags","id":"11272"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25638"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74275"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following biochemical changes is characteristic of a degenerate meniscus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased proteoglycan content","Decreased collagen disorganisation","Increased water retention","Decreased proteoglycan content","Increased collagen cross-linking"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe meniscus is a fibrocartilaginous structure in the knee joint that plays a crucial role in load distribution, shock absorption, and joint stability. Degeneration of the meniscus is a common condition, especially in older adults, and can lead to joint dysfunction and pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased proteoglycan content\u003C/strong\u003E. In a degenerate meniscus, there is a reduction in proteoglycan content, which leads to decreased water retention and elasticity. This contributes to the mechanical weakening of the meniscus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased proteoglycan content\u003C/strong\u003E - Degeneration is associated with a decrease, not an increase, in proteoglycans\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased collagen disorganisation\u003C/strong\u003E - Degeneration typically involves increased disorganisation of collagen fibres\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased water retention\u003C/strong\u003E - Reduced proteoglycans lead to decreased water retention\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased collagen cross-linking\u003C/strong\u003E - Degeneration is associated with collagen disorganisation rather than increased cross-linking\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese changes contribute to the reduced mechanical function and increased susceptibility to damage in a degenerate meniscus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A degenerate meniscus is associated with decreased proteoglycan content, leading to reduced water retention and elasticity.","Collagen disorganisation in a degenerate meniscus contributes to its reduced mechanical strength.","Degeneration of the meniscus can lead to increased contact pressure on the joint surfaces."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Datta HK, Ng WF, Walker JA, Tuck SP, Varanasi SS. The cell biology of bone metabolism. J Clin Pathol. 2008 May;61(5):577-87. doi: 10.1136/jcp.2007.048868. PMID: 18441154","Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59766"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18330"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59766"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T04:08:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T04:08:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11048"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74275"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descript